        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong
              >Summary: Arab Gulf states are in a position to mediate the
              Israel-Iran war to pursue their strategic ambitions.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> The Arab Gulf states leveraged their
            energy wealth and the central position between East and West to
            establish themselves as economic and logistics hubs. This rise came
            with a goal: to reduce tensions in the region and focus on national
            development. However, the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-analysis-h1-8-12-day-iran-israel-war"
              target="_blank"
              >12-day Iran-Israel war</a
            >
            has gripped the Arab Gulf.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The strategies:</strong> Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and Oman aim
            to serve as mediators in the US-Iran nuclear talks. Qatar already
            played a role in ending the war by absorbing
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-analysis-h1-9-iran-s-symbolic-attack"
              target="_blank"
              >Iranâ€™s symbolic attack</a
            >, which has significantly boosted its credibility with Tehran. Iran
            sees Oman as a trusted mediator, while Saudi Arabia and the UAE
            still hold some influence in Washington. The Arab Gulf statesâ€™ core
            strategic interest remains the same: to prevent any single country
            from dominating the region.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The challenges:</strong> A significant concern is that, like
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-analysis-h1-10-iraq-in-the-1990s"
              target="_blank"
              >Iraq in the 1990s</a
            >, Iran may try to hide parts of its nuclear program. It is still
            unclear how much damage Israeli and US strikes caused to Iranâ€™s
            nuclear facilities, or what happened to its stockpile of 60%
            enriched uranium hexafluoride (a gas used to produce weapons-grade
            uranium).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Israelâ€™s military strategy, known as the
            <a
