          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              At the Jokkmok conference (an annual gathering in Sweden), the
              leaders emphasized that the Sami are one people, whose unity
              should not be broken by national borders. Source: Detroit
              Publishing/Library of Congress via Britannica
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The people:</strong> The Sami are
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-foundations-h1-18-the-indigenous-people"
              target="_blank"
              >the Indigenous people</a
            >
            of Sapmi, a region covering northern Norway, Sweden, Finland, and
            the Kola Peninsula in Russia. They are the oldest cultural group in
            much of Northern Europe. Their traditions are closely tied to
            nature, reindeer herding, fishing, and crafting. The Sami speak a
            language that is part of the Uralic (related to Finnish) language
            family, along with Finnish, Estonian, and Hungarian.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The representation:</strong>
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-foundations-h1-19-sami-parliamentary-council"
              target="_blank"
              >Sami Parliamentary Council</a
            >
            fosters cooperation across borders, which is crucial for
            strengthening Sami autonomy in national and regional decisions.
            Norway, Sweden, and Finland also have Sami parliaments, which
            promote Sami culture, language, and political rights while advising
            authorities on policies that affect Sami communities.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The challenges:</strong> Russia does not officially
            recognize the Sami as Indigenous with special rights, and existing
            laws in Norway, Sweden, and Finland often fall short in protecting
            their autonomy and culture. Expansion of mining, tourism, and
            infrastructure threatens their traditional lands and reindeer
            herding. Climate change worsens these pressures, while insufficient
            economic opportunities drive young Sami to move away, leading to
            depopulation of rural communities.
          </p>
